[normal] adjoins my own. I offered to buy the land well above grade 1 farming land price. The council reported to councillors that the land could not be used as farming land 
[normal]and denied the existence of a
[normal] letter from me offering to buy it. I cannot see how this is 
[normal]not a significant injustice. It denied me the potential opportunity to enter negotiations with the landowner. I can’t see how denying me the right to run a business is not a significant injustice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As you can see from the above commentary, I think the 
[normal]Ombudsman is guilty of a dereliction of duty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Ombudsman’s final decision notice.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1. In deciding that she would not investigate my 
[normal]2
[normal]nd
[normal] 
[normal]complaint
[normal] (re BE/151/11)
[normal], the ombudsman cites two reasons:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a) that 
[normal]‘the ombudsman cannot look
[normal] into a complaint once court action has commenced.’ I do not believe this is true. The legislation (local government act 1974, s26 para 6) says that “a
[normal] Local Commissioner shall not conduct an investigation under this Part of this Act in respect of any of t
[normal]he following matters, that is to say... 
[normal](c) any action in respect of which the person aggrieved has or had a remedy by way of proceedings in any court of law. Provided that a Local Commissioner may conduct an investigation notwithstanding the existence of 
[normal]such a right or remedy if satisfied that in the particular circumstances it is not reasonable to expect the person aggrieved to resort or have resorted to it.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Firstly, i
[normal]n this instance I only resorted to requesting a judicial review as the LGO had refus
[normal]ed to investigate the original request for assistance in dealing with the matter
[normal] – if the LGO had performed her duty the JR would not have been necessary
[normal]. 
[normal]Secondly, I was unable to exercise my right as, having lodged the request for a judicial review, it b
[normal]ecame clear that I was unable to fund even a commentary on the Council’s defence. Therefore it was not reasonable for me to pursue the JR and I did not have a remedy in a court of law. In addition, 
[normal]the council with
[normal]held
[normal] information
[normal] necessary for a judicial 
[normal]review
[normal]. This was finally extracted by the ICO just a couple of days after the judge decided not to hear the case. In refusing a JR the judge made it clear that he
[normal] did so ’given the realities following the grant of the fourth application’. This 
[normal]would 
[normal]have b
[normal]een very different had the LGO been prepared to investigate the planning. I am a basic rate taxpayer and spent £6,000 on a very basic application. I was simply unable to afford further rebutting of the council’s 
[normal]untrue 
[normal]defence. 
