[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Brief history of the planning applications[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]BE/42/10 for a caravan park on Grade 1 agricultural land was approved under delegated powers by Arun
[normal] District Council officers. Residents were unable to complain as none saw the application site notices. The Council claims that the notices were there and inspected – but had to guess at four different inspection dates before alighting on a date that was e
[normal]ven possible.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In granting BE/42/10 officers:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Bec
[normal]ause the applicant developed something entirely different to BE/42/10 – for instance he developed a much bigger piece of land, knocked down a screening wall, enlargened the entrance and put it right next to his neighbours and place the caravan pads within 
[normal]a few metres of neighbours windows – thus blocking their light, BE/151/11 was submitted.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BE/151/11 was an attempt to regularise the previous breaches of planning permission, but in fact created more breaches. In creating and approving (the applicant claim
[normal]s that officers assisted with the development of the plans) BE/151/11, officers:
[normal]All these errors were pointed out to planners before their presentation to councillors and councillors 
[normal]were told by planners that all of these statements made by residents’ were untrue.
